00:00:06.200 --> 00:00:08.970
SPEAKER 1: So let's
start at the beginning.

00:00:08.970 --> 00:00:13.040
So Arno, in the late
'80s, early '90s,

00:00:13.040 --> 00:00:15.140
you were a founding
member of what

00:00:15.140 --> 00:00:17.600
went on to become one
of the largest hate

00:00:17.600 --> 00:00:20.280
groups in the country.

00:00:20.280 --> 00:00:23.090
Tell us about your experience
in Milwaukee, growing up,

00:00:23.090 --> 00:00:27.141
and that led to being involved
in an organization like that.

00:00:27.141 --> 00:00:29.390
ARNO MICHAELIS: What's
interesting about my experience

00:00:29.390 --> 00:00:31.670
is that on paper,
I would have been

00:00:31.670 --> 00:00:33.170
like the last kid
you would think

00:00:33.170 --> 00:00:35.310
that would go that direction.

00:00:35.310 --> 00:00:37.580
When I was researching
for my first book,

00:00:37.580 --> 00:00:40.220
I was talking to a lot of people
who were in the gang with me

00:00:40.220 --> 00:00:43.820
and who had also gotten
out, and in the process

00:00:43.820 --> 00:00:45.980
of doing that, I was asking
about their childhoods,

00:00:45.980 --> 00:00:48.170
asking about things that
they'd been through.

00:00:48.170 --> 00:00:51.980
And just about all of them
had horrific childhoods.

00:00:51.980 --> 00:00:53.630
There was missing parents.

00:00:53.630 --> 00:00:55.980
There was physical abuse.

00:00:55.980 --> 00:00:57.530
There was poverty.

00:00:57.530 --> 00:01:00.620
In my case, I grew up in a nice
house, in a nice neighborhood,

00:01:00.620 --> 00:01:02.480
never went hungry,
never took a beating.

00:01:02.480 --> 00:01:03.620
My parents were together.

00:01:03.620 --> 00:01:05.810
They both loved me very much.

00:01:05.810 --> 00:01:07.920
They let me know
that all the time.

00:01:07.920 --> 00:01:09.590
In fact, all the
adults in my life

00:01:09.590 --> 00:01:13.760
were just showering me with
affirmation and positivity.

00:01:13.760 --> 00:01:15.860
But I grew up in an
alcoholic household,

00:01:15.860 --> 00:01:17.540
and my parents fought a lot.

00:01:17.540 --> 00:01:19.190
And my mom was
always stressed out,

00:01:19.190 --> 00:01:21.650
trying to keep things running.

00:01:21.650 --> 00:01:26.630
And my mom's misery
was very plain to me.

00:01:26.630 --> 00:01:29.829
And instead of being a
good kid, and being like,

00:01:29.829 --> 00:01:31.370
hey, mom, I love
you, how can I help,

00:01:31.370 --> 00:01:34.730
I would be distancing myself
from her, distancing myself

00:01:34.730 --> 00:01:37.820
from my dad, from all these
adults who were supporting me,

00:01:37.820 --> 00:01:39.950
which of course,
made me suffer more

00:01:39.950 --> 00:01:44.540
and led me to start lashing out
at other kids which I quickly

00:01:44.540 --> 00:01:45.560
got a habit for.

00:01:45.560 --> 00:01:48.410
I got a habit for
people being afraid

00:01:48.410 --> 00:01:52.100
of me, a habit for the thrill
of teachers freaking out,

00:01:52.100 --> 00:01:56.240
of causing havoc in
otherwise orderly places.

00:01:56.240 --> 00:02:00.320
And like any kind of substance
abuse, what gets you high

00:02:00.320 --> 00:02:02.870
the first time is old
hat 10 times later.

00:02:02.870 --> 00:02:04.700
You got to keep escalating it.

00:02:04.700 --> 00:02:07.550
So my anti-social
behavior escalated

00:02:07.550 --> 00:02:09.160
from being a bully
on the school bus

00:02:09.160 --> 00:02:12.170
to fights in the school yard
to breaking and entering,

00:02:12.170 --> 00:02:15.560
burglary, vandalism,
fighting in the street.

00:02:15.560 --> 00:02:18.200
I started drinking
myself when I was 14.

00:02:18.200 --> 00:02:20.750
The first time I drank, I
drank until I passed out,

00:02:20.750 --> 00:02:23.240
and I drank like that
for another 20 years.

00:02:23.240 --> 00:02:26.450
By the time I'm 16, I'm
a full-blown alcoholic.

00:02:26.450 --> 00:02:28.790
I am very conditioned
to violence.

00:02:28.790 --> 00:02:30.650
It's like second nature to me.

00:02:30.650 --> 00:02:33.380
And hate is just another
part of the thrill,

00:02:33.380 --> 00:02:35.850
like just, oh, I
hate the school.

00:02:35.850 --> 00:02:36.590
I hate the cops.

00:02:36.590 --> 00:02:37.235
I hate society.

00:02:37.235 --> 00:02:38.400
I hate the government.

00:02:38.400 --> 00:02:40.910
Like it was just
part of the habit

00:02:40.910 --> 00:02:43.520
that I was really addicted to.

00:02:43.520 --> 00:02:46.700
And so that's who I was when
I heard white power skinhead

00:02:46.700 --> 00:02:50.910
music that was really fast
and aggressive, which I loved.

00:02:50.910 --> 00:02:53.900
I was in a punk before that,
and I loved the hardcore fast

00:02:53.900 --> 00:02:56.120
break stuff kind of punk.

00:02:56.120 --> 00:02:58.100
And this was the
same kind of music,

00:02:58.100 --> 00:03:02.540
but the lyrics were about race
and nation and blood and soil,

00:03:02.540 --> 00:03:06.500
all these very seductive
and romantic themes,

00:03:06.500 --> 00:03:08.930
and the same themes, really,
that Adolf Hitler used

00:03:08.930 --> 00:03:11.770
to twist the mind of so
many millions of Germans

00:03:11.770 --> 00:03:14.120
in World War II.

00:03:14.120 --> 00:03:16.790
Plus, it really
pissed people off.

00:03:16.790 --> 00:03:19.550
Nothing pisses people
off like a swastika.

00:03:19.550 --> 00:03:22.610
And I was just really in the
business of pissing people off.

00:03:22.610 --> 00:03:24.170
That's all I wanted to do.

00:03:24.170 --> 00:03:27.170
So my initial involvement in
these white power skinhead

00:03:27.170 --> 00:03:29.500
hate groups was to get
a rise out of people.

00:03:29.500 --> 00:03:34.370
It was to repulse civil society
and to provoke hostility,

00:03:34.370 --> 00:03:35.600
to provoke fights.

00:03:35.600 --> 00:03:38.916
So that's what got me into it.

00:03:38.916 --> 00:03:41.040
Me and a couple of friends
started this white power

00:03:41.040 --> 00:03:42.740
skinhead gang in Milwaukee.

00:03:42.740 --> 00:03:45.140
I was already in
punk bands and pretty

00:03:45.140 --> 00:03:47.690
acclimated to screaming loud
and getting people crazy.

00:03:47.690 --> 00:03:50.360
So we started our
own skinhead band,

00:03:50.360 --> 00:03:52.460
and we were like a
magnet for pissed

00:03:52.460 --> 00:03:55.670
off white kids that just
came from every direction

00:03:55.670 --> 00:03:57.980
to be part of what
we were doing.

00:03:57.980 --> 00:04:02.150
And as we radiated
hostility into the world,

00:04:02.150 --> 00:04:04.970
the world reflected it
back to us, and oftentimes

00:04:04.970 --> 00:04:06.260
in multiples.

00:04:06.260 --> 00:04:09.269
And within a few
months, my best friend,

00:04:09.269 --> 00:04:11.060
who I'd started the
gang and the band with,

00:04:11.060 --> 00:04:13.970
went to prison for shooting
a kid who came into a drive

00:04:13.970 --> 00:04:15.140
by our house.

00:04:15.140 --> 00:04:18.214
Within a couple of years,
another very good friend

00:04:18.214 --> 00:04:20.089
of mine was shot and
killed in a street fight

00:04:20.089 --> 00:04:22.370
as he was out practicing
hate and violence,

00:04:22.370 --> 00:04:24.710
as I had taught him to do.

00:04:24.710 --> 00:04:27.380
And rather than see these
bad things happening

00:04:27.380 --> 00:04:31.130
as wake-up calls, we
saw them as validation

00:04:31.130 --> 00:04:33.080
of our paranoid narrative.

00:04:33.080 --> 00:04:37.040
So rather than wake up
and come to my senses

00:04:37.040 --> 00:04:39.549
when my friend got murdered,
it wasn't his fault

00:04:39.549 --> 00:04:42.090
that he was out marching around
with a swastika on his jacket

00:04:42.090 --> 00:04:44.600
and picking fights with people
that led to the shooting that

00:04:44.600 --> 00:04:45.560
killed him.

00:04:45.560 --> 00:04:48.320
It was the Jews'
fault for bringing

00:04:48.320 --> 00:04:50.070
all these black and
brown people here.

00:04:50.070 --> 00:04:52.940
And so that whole
way of thinking

00:04:52.940 --> 00:04:56.630
is this constant
process of spinning

00:04:56.630 --> 00:04:59.960
whatever's happening in the
world to suit your narrative.

00:04:59.960 --> 00:05:03.937
And it took a ton of
energy and really added

00:05:03.937 --> 00:05:05.395
to this growing
sense of exhaustion

00:05:05.395 --> 00:05:07.000
that eventually led me out.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:10.450
SPEAKER 1: And Pardeep, you
had a different upbringing

00:05:10.450 --> 00:05:11.160
in Milwaukee.

00:05:11.160 --> 00:05:13.060
So talk about your
time and really--

00:05:13.060 --> 00:05:15.430
I know you were a police
officer for a while-- to where

00:05:15.430 --> 00:05:18.100
you are today, but really
the growing up in Milwaukee

00:05:18.100 --> 00:05:20.080
and what it was like
for you and your family.

00:05:20.080 --> 00:05:21.930
PARDEEP KALEKA: Yeah,
for us in our family,

00:05:21.930 --> 00:05:25.450
I came to the states
when I was six years old.

00:05:25.450 --> 00:05:27.530
And I had sort of a typical--

00:05:27.530 --> 00:05:29.170
and now, I want to
use the word typical

00:05:29.170 --> 00:05:32.290
right now because I think the
time and space that we exist

00:05:32.290 --> 00:05:38.320
in right now calls for a
unity of just immigration

00:05:38.320 --> 00:05:40.840
and immigration patterns,
demographic change.

00:05:40.840 --> 00:05:44.600
And so I grew up as
your typical immigrant.

00:05:44.600 --> 00:05:48.430
I came here when I was six, not
a lot of money in our pockets.

00:05:48.430 --> 00:05:52.280
My dad had $10 in his pocket--

00:05:52.280 --> 00:05:54.880
maybe $35 in his pocket--

00:05:54.880 --> 00:06:00.280
probably a little bit more,
but just scratching, clawing.

00:06:00.280 --> 00:06:01.720
We moved to
Milwaukee, Wisconsin.

00:06:01.720 --> 00:06:06.490
At that time, in the 1980s,
Milwaukee was a thriving city.

00:06:06.490 --> 00:06:08.980
Soon as we got
here, there were be

00:06:08.980 --> 00:06:12.322
this sort of job exodus,
employment exodus

00:06:12.322 --> 00:06:13.780
in the city of
Milwaukee that would

00:06:13.780 --> 00:06:23.046
lead to kind of an illegal
economy, and just an economy--

00:06:23.046 --> 00:06:24.170
there goes the crime rates.

00:06:24.170 --> 00:06:26.110
There goes drug raids.

00:06:26.110 --> 00:06:29.740
There goes these
shootings, homicides.

00:06:29.740 --> 00:06:37.240
And before long, we were
caught in the hairs of trying

00:06:37.240 --> 00:06:40.510
to find a safe place to live.

00:06:40.510 --> 00:06:43.122
I remember my parents
moving around quite a bit.

00:06:43.122 --> 00:06:44.830
We moved from the
north side of Milwaukee

00:06:44.830 --> 00:06:47.620
to the east side of Milwaukee,
east side of Milwaukee

00:06:47.620 --> 00:06:50.800
to the south side,
west side, and really

00:06:50.800 --> 00:06:53.140
just going on this
whole journey of trying

00:06:53.140 --> 00:06:59.080
to find a safe place
to raise their kids.

00:06:59.080 --> 00:07:02.740
As I grew up, I
grew up and there

00:07:02.740 --> 00:07:05.920
wasn't a lot of Punjabi people
at that time in the '80s,

00:07:05.920 --> 00:07:07.970
especially not in
Milwaukee, Wisconsin.

00:07:07.970 --> 00:07:11.140
I think there was about
four or five families,

00:07:11.140 --> 00:07:15.940
and that, not having
somebody or some people

00:07:15.940 --> 00:07:21.130
to call your own led
to this feeling of,

00:07:21.130 --> 00:07:24.250
I wasn't enough, led
to this feeling of,

00:07:24.250 --> 00:07:25.870
I'm not black
enough to be black.

00:07:25.870 --> 00:07:28.210
I'm not Latino
enough to be Latino.

00:07:28.210 --> 00:07:30.040
I'm not white
enough to be white.

00:07:30.040 --> 00:07:32.740
I'm not American enough
to call myself American.

00:07:32.740 --> 00:07:35.410
And in a weird kind of way,
I wasn't even Indian enough

00:07:35.410 --> 00:07:38.140
to call myself Indian.

00:07:38.140 --> 00:07:42.790
I can, as a 42-year-old grown up
man, can see the beauty in that

00:07:42.790 --> 00:07:47.140
now because all of that led to
me being able to embrace myself

00:07:47.140 --> 00:07:48.280
and me.

00:07:48.280 --> 00:07:50.620
But at that time,
growing up, it really

00:07:50.620 --> 00:07:52.695
led to a sense of, who am I?

00:07:52.695 --> 00:07:53.740
What am I?

00:07:53.740 --> 00:07:55.520
What do I represent?

00:07:55.520 --> 00:07:58.840
And that led to me
saying, OK, you know what?

00:07:58.840 --> 00:08:02.620
I want to do something
with my life that's

00:08:02.620 --> 00:08:07.210
going to mean something to
the country that gave me hope.

00:08:07.210 --> 00:08:10.050
And I dreamt about
being a police officer.

00:08:10.050 --> 00:08:11.800
I became the first
one in our family

00:08:11.800 --> 00:08:17.590
to graduate from college, became
a police officer in Milwaukee,

00:08:17.590 --> 00:08:23.230
and just really
noticing some of the--

00:08:23.230 --> 00:08:25.550
and as I was growing
up, I thought the world

00:08:25.550 --> 00:08:27.210
to be black and white, right?

00:08:27.210 --> 00:08:30.700
We think in simple terms of,
I can give back to the society

00:08:30.700 --> 00:08:36.309
if I can keep good people
safe from bad folks.

00:08:36.309 --> 00:08:40.669
But we know the realities of
policing are not that simple.

00:08:40.669 --> 00:08:43.690
There's a lot of gray,
and over time, that gray

00:08:43.690 --> 00:08:46.130
became too much to stomach.

00:08:46.130 --> 00:08:50.110
And so I became a
educator working

00:08:50.110 --> 00:08:52.900
with at-risk high school
youth in the same neighborhood

00:08:52.900 --> 00:08:54.400
that I was policing.

00:08:54.400 --> 00:08:56.530
The neighborhood
that I was policing

00:08:56.530 --> 00:08:57.850
has a documentary about it.

00:08:57.850 --> 00:08:59.920
It's called 53206.

00:08:59.920 --> 00:09:03.410
It is one of the most violent
neighborhoods in Milwaukee.

00:09:03.410 --> 00:09:06.250
So the entirety of
my policing career

00:09:06.250 --> 00:09:09.760
was getting dope, getting
guns, getting arrests,

00:09:09.760 --> 00:09:11.680
and yet, throughout
that entire five years,

00:09:11.680 --> 00:09:15.610
I never wrote one parking
ticket or one speeding ticket.

00:09:15.610 --> 00:09:18.070
It was just really just
running and gunning.

00:09:18.070 --> 00:09:22.120
And seeing that from that
sense of a police officer,

00:09:22.120 --> 00:09:26.830
and then working
as a teacher, you

00:09:26.830 --> 00:09:30.560
see a different
level of intimacy.

00:09:30.560 --> 00:09:32.890
Now you're working
with youth, attempting

00:09:32.890 --> 00:09:36.700
to try to work with them
before they get into this life.

00:09:36.700 --> 00:09:39.990
And you get to know parents and
you get to know grandparents.

00:09:39.990 --> 00:09:42.402
And you have to develop
relationships, probably

00:09:42.402 --> 00:09:44.610
something that I should have
done as a police officer

00:09:44.610 --> 00:09:46.050
anyways.

00:09:46.050 --> 00:09:48.570
But we didn't live
in that culture

00:09:48.570 --> 00:09:51.190
of getting to know the
neighborhood you were policing

00:09:51.190 --> 00:09:51.750
in.

00:09:51.750 --> 00:09:54.180
It was really just running,
gunning, arresting,

00:09:54.180 --> 00:09:56.050
and that was that.

00:09:56.050 --> 00:09:59.520
And that was my life
before August 5th.

00:09:59.520 --> 00:10:01.770
