00:20:19.260 --> 00:20:21.510
No bigger martyrdom.

00:20:21.510 --> 00:20:22.500
We call it sahidi.

00:20:22.500 --> 00:20:26.130
Some people call it kabani,
but no bigger sacrifice

00:20:26.130 --> 00:20:28.407
than a person
could do than that.

00:20:28.407 --> 00:20:30.573
And in fact, I had a lot
of people who came up to me

00:20:30.573 --> 00:20:33.130
and were like, don't feel bad.

00:20:33.130 --> 00:20:34.530
Don't feel sad.

00:20:34.530 --> 00:20:36.940
Just, your dad did
what he needed to do.

00:20:36.940 --> 00:20:42.000
And no better death than to
die that death of a martyr.

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:44.760
With that said, that puts
a lot of pressure on you

00:20:44.760 --> 00:20:49.380
as the oldest son, and
puts a lot of pressure

00:20:49.380 --> 00:20:53.350
on what you need to do.

00:20:53.350 --> 00:20:57.450
So my personal grief,
my personal healing,

00:20:57.450 --> 00:20:59.310
could not actually start.

00:20:59.310 --> 00:21:03.420
I had to figure out
logistics for other families

00:21:03.420 --> 00:21:05.490
who had lost their loved ones.

00:21:05.490 --> 00:21:08.190
Most of these families
did not understand

00:21:08.190 --> 00:21:09.666
the culture of America.

00:21:09.666 --> 00:21:11.040
So I was old enough
to understand

00:21:11.040 --> 00:21:15.930
the culture of America, how do
we do funeral proceedings, who

00:21:15.930 --> 00:21:18.960
pays for what, the
logistics of everything.

00:21:18.960 --> 00:21:21.240
How do we raise funds?

00:21:21.240 --> 00:21:24.000
This thing that I felt,
I felt in my mind,

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:27.610
was just to dive into work.

00:21:27.610 --> 00:21:31.680
With that said, we basically put
on a brave face for the world,

00:21:31.680 --> 00:21:32.760
right?

00:21:32.760 --> 00:21:36.270
But at the same time, I
think I was faking it.

00:21:36.270 --> 00:21:37.650
I think I wasn't truly--

00:21:37.650 --> 00:21:39.060
I was still bitter.

00:21:39.060 --> 00:21:40.450
I was still upset.

00:21:40.450 --> 00:21:44.340
I was still gritting my teeth
at every interview where they

00:21:44.340 --> 00:21:46.110
would talk about forgiveness.

00:21:46.110 --> 00:21:49.170
And I'd be like, oh, fah.

00:21:49.170 --> 00:21:50.880
Yes.

00:21:50.880 --> 00:21:54.420
Let me talk about this.

00:21:54.420 --> 00:21:56.250
And that was my honest truth.

00:21:56.250 --> 00:21:58.320
I did a thing for law
enforcement one time

00:21:58.320 --> 00:22:00.360
and I could barely
get through the talk

00:22:00.360 --> 00:22:02.790
because I was so bitter.

00:22:02.790 --> 00:22:09.130
And when we were doing this,
