brawl or something?

00:37:33.970 --> 00:37:38.030
Par goes on to tell me
that a week earlier, he's

00:37:38.030 --> 00:37:41.720
bathing his son and daughter,
and his wife's at work.

00:37:41.720 --> 00:37:42.740
His daughter is 7.

00:37:42.740 --> 00:37:44.450
His son was 4.

00:37:44.450 --> 00:37:47.270
And his daughter is
getting to the stage,

00:37:47.270 --> 00:37:50.270
as a little kid, of being
self-conscious about being

00:37:50.270 --> 00:37:51.230
naked.

00:37:51.230 --> 00:37:53.210
So she's like, dad,
when I'm taking a bath,

00:37:53.210 --> 00:37:54.970
don't look at me.

00:37:54.970 --> 00:37:57.560
And Par's like, he wants
to oblige his daughter,

00:37:57.560 --> 00:37:59.540
but he also needs
to get everywhere

00:37:59.540 --> 00:38:01.750
or his wife's going
to let him have it

00:38:01.750 --> 00:38:03.320
if he's not scrubbing
her down right.

00:38:03.320 --> 00:38:05.782
So he's scrubbing
while looking away,

00:38:05.782 --> 00:38:08.240
but he's got to peek and make
sure he's getting everywhere,

00:38:08.240 --> 00:38:09.920
and then peek away.

00:38:09.920 --> 00:38:13.314
Scrub, scrub, peek, peek away.

00:38:13.314 --> 00:38:15.480
In the corner of the bathtub,
he's going one of them

00:38:15.480 --> 00:38:16.442
shower organizers.

00:38:16.442 --> 00:38:18.080
It's like spring loaded.

00:38:18.080 --> 00:38:20.240
It goes between the bathroom
corner of the ceiling

00:38:20.240 --> 00:38:21.740
and you got little
shelves where you

00:38:21.740 --> 00:38:23.480
put your shampoos and whatnot.

00:38:23.480 --> 00:38:26.900
And hanging off these shelves
are these little loofa hooks.

00:38:26.900 --> 00:38:29.990
And Par's wife, Priti, is like,
Par, you got to get rid of them

00:38:29.990 --> 00:38:30.491
hooks.

00:38:30.491 --> 00:38:32.365
Somebody's going to lose
an eye or something.

00:38:32.365 --> 00:38:33.770
This is really dangerous.

00:38:33.770 --> 00:38:36.320
And Par, like many husbands,
was like, yeah, oh, sure.

00:38:36.320 --> 00:38:39.442
I'll get to it, only
he never gets to it.

00:38:39.442 --> 00:38:41.900
So as he's scrubbing and peeking
and scrubbing and peeking,

00:38:41.900 --> 00:38:45.440
he looks away and the hook
goes right into his eye,

00:38:45.440 --> 00:38:47.960
like a hot knife
through butter, just

00:38:47.960 --> 00:38:49.490
like through the
white of his eye

00:38:49.490 --> 00:38:51.810
and then out above his
eyebrow, like a fishhook.

00:38:51.810 --> 00:38:53.340
Just whoomp!

00:38:53.340 --> 00:38:57.883
And so Par's got his face
attached to this contraption

00:38:57.883 --> 00:39:00.610
and he pulls the
springs to get it out.

00:39:00.610 --> 00:39:03.430
He comes up like this
and he's holding it.

00:39:03.430 --> 00:39:05.350
What the hell am I going to do?

00:39:05.350 --> 00:39:08.070
And his daughter, Amaris, there
was freaking out and screaming.

00:39:08.070 --> 00:39:10.408
And she grabs it and
starts yanking on it.

00:39:10.408 --> 00:39:11.424
Fortunately--

00:39:11.424 --> 00:39:13.340
PARDEEP KALEKA: I could
hear my eye throbbing.

00:39:13.340 --> 00:39:17.561
I was like, the eyeball's
going to come out, baby girl.

00:39:17.561 --> 00:39:20.060
ARNO MICHAELIS: Fortunately,
Pardeep's an ex-police officer.

00:39:20.060 --> 00:39:21.530
He's very cool under pressure.

00:39:21.530 --> 00:39:25.050
So Amaris is hauling
on this hook.

00:39:25.050 --> 00:39:27.730
Pardeep's like, baby girl.

00:39:27.730 --> 00:39:30.352
You got to let go of the hook.

00:39:30.352 --> 00:39:32.699
And so she lets
go and he gets up.

00:39:32.699 --> 00:39:34.240
He goes to the mirror
and he takes it

00:39:34.240 --> 00:39:35.240
out the way it comes in.

00:39:35.240 --> 00:39:36.580
Blood goes flying everywhere.

00:39:36.580 --> 00:39:38.560
He says, OK, kids, get dressed.

00:39:38.560 --> 00:39:39.960
We're going to urgent care.

00:39:39.960 --> 00:39:42.460
There's an urgent care
a couple blocks away.

00:39:42.460 --> 00:39:44.020
He puts a towel over his eye.

00:39:44.020 --> 00:39:46.320
He's got four-year-old
Jay in one arm.

00:39:46.320 --> 00:39:48.830
He's got the phone
and the towel here.

00:39:48.830 --> 00:39:51.830
Amaris is hanging on his
belt. He calls his wife

00:39:51.830 --> 00:39:54.010
as he walked into urgent care.

00:39:54.010 --> 00:39:55.870
Hey, honey, yeah.

00:39:55.870 --> 00:39:57.640
You know that hook in the bath?

00:39:57.640 --> 00:39:59.830
Yeah, you're going to
say, I told you so,

00:39:59.830 --> 00:40:02.720
but yeah, it went in my eye.

00:40:02.720 --> 00:40:04.430
She's like, you idiot.

00:40:04.430 --> 00:40:06.970
So he gets to urgent
care, comes walking in.

00:40:06.970 --> 00:40:08.040
They're like, nope, nope.

00:40:08.040 --> 00:40:09.700
You got to go to
the emergency room.

00:40:09.700 --> 00:40:10.840
We can't help you here.

00:40:10.840 --> 00:40:12.452
PARDEEP KALEKA: We
don't see those.

00:40:12.452 --> 00:40:13.910
ARNO MICHAELIS: So
just then, Priti

00:40:13.910 --> 00:40:16.939
gets there, once again,
probably called you an idiot.

00:40:16.939 --> 00:40:17.980
PARDEEP KALEKA: Oh, yeah.

00:40:17.980 --> 00:40:20.010
ARNO MICHAELIS: It's an
I told you so moment.

00:40:20.010 --> 00:40:25.090
Takes him to the real doctor,
and they take the hook out,

00:40:25.090 --> 00:40:26.700
and the doctor's
like, Pardeep, you

00:40:26.700 --> 00:40:29.695
are one of the luckiest people
I've ever met in my life.

00:40:29.695 --> 00:40:31.880
And Pardeep's like, I don't
really feel very lucky.

00:40:31.880 --> 00:40:33.421
And the doctor goes,
if it would have

00:40:33.421 --> 00:40:36.280
been 2 millimeters the other
way, you'd have a glass eye.

00:40:36.280 --> 00:40:40.300
But as it was, his eye was
OK, but it tore the muscle

00:40:40.300 --> 00:40:42.400
that kept his eyelid up.

00:40:42.400 --> 00:40:45.730
So like in true
Punjabi fabulousness,

00:40:45.730 --> 00:40:49.790
he tapes his eyelid
up so he can see,

00:40:49.790 --> 00:40:52.580
and then he's got
to manually blink,

00:40:52.580 --> 00:40:55.780
bringing his bottom eyelid
up when the eye gets dry.

00:40:55.780 --> 00:40:57.060
And so he tells me this story.

00:40:57.060 --> 00:40:58.530
And I'm just like
all y'all were.

00:40:58.530 --> 00:41:01.370
I'm just like, oh, ew, no.

00:41:01.370 --> 00:41:05.530
I'm literally squirming
and feeling his pain.

00:41:05.530 --> 00:41:09.660
And this empathy that I have for
the suffering he went through

00:41:09.660 --> 00:41:14.080
on the spot just like broke
the ice, on both sides.

00:41:14.080 --> 00:41:18.040
And for me also, I'm like
an almost fatal klutz.

00:41:18.040 --> 00:41:19.970
Like I am my own worst enemy.

00:41:19.970 --> 00:41:22.270
I have over 20 concussions,
and probably half of them

00:41:22.270 --> 00:41:23.890
are self induced.

00:41:23.890 --> 00:41:26.260
And so when he's telling
me about his klutziness,

00:41:26.260 --> 00:41:28.170
I'm like this is my guy.

00:41:28.170 --> 00:41:30.980
We've been separated at birth.

00:41:30.980 --> 00:41:34.520
So we sat down and we
split some squash curry.

00:41:34.520 --> 00:41:36.444
Spicy was level 7, I believe.

00:41:36.444 --> 00:41:37.360
It was pretty banging.

00:41:37.360 --> 00:41:40.267
PARDEEP KALEKA:
And we got drunk.

00:41:40.267 --> 00:41:42.600
ARNO MICHAELIS: We were
actually drinking tea all night.

00:41:42.600 --> 00:41:44.860
We got buzzed on
those places for sure.

00:41:44.860 --> 00:41:46.110
We were pretty buzzed.

00:41:46.110 --> 00:41:48.880
And I remember, we met at
6 PM and the restaurant

00:41:48.880 --> 00:41:50.470
closes at 9 PM.

00:41:50.470 --> 00:41:54.120
And it was almost 10
when King's like, Arno,

00:41:54.120 --> 00:41:56.310
we closed like 45 minutes ago.

00:41:56.310 --> 00:41:57.690
Could you guys wrap it up?

00:41:57.690 --> 00:41:59.570
And it was amazing.

00:41:59.570 --> 00:42:03.406
We just had this brilliant
discussion that was so open,

00:42:03.406 --> 00:42:04.780
and throughout
this conversation,

00:42:04.780 --> 00:42:05.710
I have to remind myself.

00:42:05.710 --> 00:42:08.043
I'm like, dude, you're sitting
here talking to this dude

00:42:08.043 --> 00:42:10.510
because one of your old
guys murdered his dad.

00:42:10.510 --> 00:42:15.450
Because Par was so down to earth
and so genuine and so friendly.

00:42:15.450 --> 00:42:17.470
We just had the
most amazing talk.

00:42:17.470 --> 00:42:20.419
And as we talked, we
saw we had so much more

00:42:20.419 --> 00:42:22.210
in common than different,
even though we're

00:42:22.210 --> 00:42:25.000
born on opposite
sides of the planet.

00:42:25.000 --> 00:42:27.940
Our family stories are
the polar opposite.

00:42:27.940 --> 00:42:30.700
His family scrapped and clawed
to achieve the American dream

00:42:30.700 --> 00:42:32.290
over 30 years.

00:42:32.290 --> 00:42:34.180
I was born with the
American dream handed

00:42:34.180 --> 00:42:35.410
to me on a silver platter.

00:42:35.410 --> 00:42:38.320
All I had to do was execute,
and I spent my whole life

00:42:38.320 --> 00:42:39.800
getting away from it.

00:42:39.800 --> 00:42:43.390
But as we sat and talked, like
commonality after commonality

00:42:43.390 --> 00:42:47.024
after commonality appeared,
to the point of where he was

00:42:47.024 --> 00:42:48.190
saying his daughter's seven.

00:42:48.190 --> 00:42:49.731
I'm like, when my
daughter was seven,

00:42:49.731 --> 00:42:52.120
she had this thing
with her socks.

00:42:52.120 --> 00:42:55.930
And you'd put her socks on, and
if that seam was like cocked

00:42:55.930 --> 00:42:57.682
what-- you know
what I'm saying--

00:42:57.682 --> 00:43:00.240
if it's cocked one way or
the other over her toes,

00:43:00.240 --> 00:43:03.220
she'd just be like this and
just freeze and not go anywhere.

00:43:03.220 --> 00:43:06.064
You got to take her shoes
off, put the socks back on.

00:43:06.064 --> 00:43:07.480
And I'm telling
him that, and he's

00:43:07.480 --> 00:43:09.670
like, my daughter does that.

00:43:09.670 --> 00:43:11.320
We're talking about our dads.

00:43:11.320 --> 00:43:15.367
Par's dad would never pay
anybody to fix nothing.

00:43:15.367 --> 00:43:16.950
Whether he knows how
to fix it or not,

00:43:16.950 --> 00:43:18.416
he's like, I'm
going to fix this.

00:43:18.416 --> 00:43:21.070
This results in him
having the lawn mower

00:43:21.070 --> 00:43:23.920
in pieces on the living room
carpet in the middle of winter,

00:43:23.920 --> 00:43:25.510
much to his mother's horror.

00:43:25.510 --> 00:43:28.490
And my dad did the
exact same thing.

00:43:28.490 --> 00:43:30.400
So after all these
commonalities,

00:43:30.400 --> 00:43:33.400
that was really where the idea
for Serve to Unite was born.

00:43:33.400 --> 00:43:35.965
And we walked out of
there right away like we

00:43:35.965 --> 00:43:37.240
were going to work together.

00:43:37.240 --> 00:43:38.470
We're going to be doing
something together

00:43:38.470 --> 00:43:39.524
from this point forward.

00:43:39.524 --> 00:43:41.440
SPEAKER 1: So I want to
get to Serve to Unite,

00:43:41.440 --> 00:43:44.020
but we do have
two mics, so we'll

00:43:44.020 --> 00:43:45.200
get to audience questions.

00:43:45.200 --> 00:43:46.919
So if people want
to start lining up.

00:43:46.919 --> 00:43:49.210
But talk to us about Serve
to Unite, how you founded it

00:43:49.210 --> 00:43:50.990
and the message of
your foundation.

00:43:50.990 --> 00:43:52.350
PARDEEP KALEKA: Sure.

00:43:52.350 --> 00:43:54.730
So Serve to Unite
was founded, I mean,

00:43:54.730 --> 00:43:58.250
in response to the Sikh temple
shootings on August 5th.

00:43:58.250 --> 00:44:02.085
And what we saw at that time
in Oak Creek, Wisconsin,

00:44:02.085 --> 00:44:04.090
and it's still
happening right now,

00:44:04.090 --> 00:44:06.540
is we were seeing a lot
of demographic change.

00:44:06.540 --> 00:44:08.350
And we saw a lot of
people uncomfortable

00:44:08.350 --> 00:44:10.150
with this demographic change.

00:44:10.150 --> 00:44:13.180
And as we've been,
for the last six years

00:44:13.180 --> 00:44:15.430
that we've been
traveling, we've been

00:44:15.430 --> 00:44:18.460
able to go to many
communities around the United

00:44:18.460 --> 00:44:20.980
States, small towns
who are uncomfortable

00:44:20.980 --> 00:44:23.132
with this demographic change.

00:44:23.132 --> 00:44:27.130
And so Serve to Unite was
really just to respond to that.

00:44:27.130 --> 00:44:29.020
And eventually what
it started to do

00:44:29.020 --> 00:44:32.560
was, in the spirit of
intentions, sometimes

00:44:32.560 --> 00:44:35.840
intentions take you
into different spheres.

00:44:35.840 --> 00:44:38.197
And then we started to get
into conversations about, OK,

00:44:38.197 --> 00:44:40.030
how do we bring school
communities together?

00:44:40.030 --> 00:44:42.220
How do we bring broad
communities together?

00:44:42.220 --> 00:44:44.510
How do we bring global
communities together?

00:44:44.510 --> 00:44:47.670
And that's really
where Serve to Unite--

00:44:47.670 --> 00:44:50.500
it is an organization, but
it's much more a calling.

00:44:50.500 --> 00:44:53.220
And it's a calling, not
to say, you know what?

00:44:53.220 --> 00:44:56.020
Serve to Unite, meaning oneness.

00:44:56.020 --> 00:44:58.950
We as human beings
have to understand,

00:44:58.950 --> 00:45:04.150
and the principles of
Christianity, Islam, Sikhism,

00:45:04.150 --> 00:45:06.850
Judaism, all those
faiths, that we are

00:45:06.850 --> 00:45:09.850
connected at a spiritual level.

00:45:09.850 --> 00:45:13.360
And it makes no sense
to read anything else

00:45:13.360 --> 00:45:18.340
into any scriptures that closes
you off rather than opens you

00:45:18.340 --> 00:45:20.500
up to that fundamental truth.

00:45:20.500 --> 00:45:25.540
And so that's what
Serve to Unite was, is,

00:45:25.540 --> 00:45:27.700
and we were privileged
to be able to go

00:45:27.700 --> 00:45:29.920
to different communities
and school communities

00:45:29.920 --> 00:45:34.347
and be able to address some of
the rift that exists right now.

00:45:34.347 --> 00:45:36.430
ARNO MICHAELIS: What we
do specifically in schools

00:45:36.430 --> 00:45:40.670
is we do arts-driven service
learning and global engagement.

00:45:40.670 --> 00:45:43.630
So we ask our students
what issues in society

00:45:43.630 --> 00:45:45.070
they want to
address, and then we

00:45:45.070 --> 00:45:47.350
facilitate service
learning projects,

00:45:47.350 --> 00:45:50.570
often involving the arts,
to solve those problems.

00:45:50.570 --> 00:45:52.330
So our students have
addressed things

00:45:52.330 --> 00:45:56.080
like community police
relations, Islamophobia,

00:45:56.080 --> 00:45:59.320
religious intolerance, racism,
homophobia, homelessness,

00:45:59.320 --> 00:46:01.420
human trafficking,
genocide prevention,

00:46:01.420 --> 00:46:03.040
Holocaust education.

00:46:03.040 --> 00:46:06.280
And we do this in conjunction
with a really amazing roster

00:46:06.280 --> 00:46:08.950
of people we call
global mentors, who

00:46:08.950 --> 00:46:10.600
are people from
all over the world,

00:46:10.600 --> 00:46:12.650
some former violent
extremists like myself,

00:46:12.650 --> 00:46:16.420
some survivors like Pardeep,
all of whom have amazing stories

00:46:16.420 --> 00:46:19.240
and do amazing work
in their own spheres.

00:46:19.240 --> 00:46:23.890
We connect them live with our
students via Google Hangout,

00:46:23.890 --> 00:46:27.520
and our students are then
like inspired by that story,

00:46:27.520 --> 00:46:31.300
and also advise in a really
practical sense about how

00:46:31.300 --> 00:46:34.150
to best carry out
these service projects.

00:46:34.150 --> 00:46:36.310
The dean Uman Yana is
a dear friend of ours

00:46:36.310 --> 00:46:38.440
and who's also appeared
on Google Talks,

00:46:38.440 --> 00:46:40.150
a survivor of the
Rwandan genocide,

00:46:40.150 --> 00:46:42.730
is one of our best
global mentors.

00:46:42.730 --> 00:46:46.264
And she helps make all
this kind of stuff happen.

00:46:46.264 --> 00:46:47.305
SPEAKER 1: Want to start?

00:46:47.305 --> 00:46:47.740
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:46:47.740 --> 00:46:48.590
Thank you so much for coming.

00:46:48.590 --> 00:46:50.840
I really appreciate you
coming and sharing your story.

00:46:50.840 --> 00:46:53.230
Arno, you describe
an adolescence

00:46:53.230 --> 00:46:55.045
that is very
hateful and violent,

00:46:55.045 --> 00:46:58.510
but at the time of August
5th, your first reaction

00:46:58.510 --> 00:46:59.800
is compassion.

00:46:59.800 --> 00:47:03.340
As maybe an insight as to how
that transformation happens

00:47:03.340 --> 00:47:05.170
to other people in
white supremacy orgs,

00:47:05.170 --> 00:47:06.230
what was your story?

00:47:06.230 --> 00:47:08.410
How did that transition
happen and how did you

00:47:08.410 --> 00:47:10.030
escape that life?

00:47:10.030 --> 00:47:12.390
ARNO MICHAELIS: That's
an awesome question.

00:47:12.390 --> 00:47:15.370
The very quick answer to
how I got out of the moment

00:47:15.370 --> 00:47:16.780
was exhaustion.

00:47:16.780 --> 00:47:19.030
It was exhausting doing
that constant spin.

00:47:19.030 --> 00:47:23.020
It was exhausting cutting myself
off from culture and media

00:47:23.020 --> 00:47:25.300
that I had once
taken for granted.

00:47:25.300 --> 00:47:26.680
What was most
exhausting was when

00:47:26.680 --> 00:47:29.590
people who I claimed to hate
treated me with kindness.

00:47:29.590 --> 00:47:32.530
And I was very fortunate that
during my seven-year span

00:47:32.530 --> 00:47:35.860
in hate groups, there were times
when a Jewish boss, a lesbian

00:47:35.860 --> 00:47:38.530
supervisor, black
and Latino coworkers,

00:47:38.530 --> 00:47:41.490
treated me with kindness
when I least deserved it.

00:47:41.490 --> 00:47:45.550
And I think this is crucial to
say, in our political climate

00:47:45.550 --> 00:47:48.130
today, in treating
me with kindness,

00:47:48.130 --> 00:47:52.360
they were actively defying
everything that I was about.

00:47:52.360 --> 00:47:55.460
Everything I did back then
was meant to provoke hatred.

00:47:55.460 --> 00:47:57.400
It was meant to
provoke hostility.

00:47:57.400 --> 00:47:59.950
If the hate was directed
at me, all the better.

00:47:59.950 --> 00:48:02.590
So when people got angry at
me and they wanted to fight,

00:48:02.590 --> 00:48:04.820
I was like, yes.

00:48:04.820 --> 00:48:07.300
Let the aggression flow.

00:48:07.300 --> 00:48:09.080
That's what I'm
trying to make happen.

00:48:09.080 --> 00:48:11.620
So the people who treated me
with kindness were like, no.

00:48:11.620 --> 00:48:13.210
You're not making
the rules here.

00:48:13.210 --> 00:48:14.410
I'm making the rules.

00:48:14.410 --> 00:48:18.130
And the rules are, this is how
human beings treat each other.

00:48:18.130 --> 00:48:21.130
If you grow up, you
can live in this world

00:48:21.130 --> 00:48:23.480
where you're not
terrified of everyone.

00:48:23.480 --> 00:48:25.200
And that's what got me out.

00:48:25.200 --> 00:48:26.734
I was very fortunate also--

00:48:26.734 --> 00:48:28.900
